WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.800
Hi, I'm Katie Macielo. I'm a Solutions Engineer at Posit. I work with customers to

00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:16.200
help them turn their data science work into applications, APIs, and reports that can be

00:00:16.200 --> 00:00:20.959
used throughout their entire organization. And I'm Ryan Johnson. I'm a Data Science

00:00:20.959 --> 00:00:26.280
Advisor here at Posit. And this year, we'll be hosting a new workshop at Posit.conf called

00:00:26.280 --> 00:00:32.119
Data Science Workflows with Posit Tools using R. And for those interested, our colleagues

00:00:32.119 --> 00:00:37.680
Sam Edwards and Gagandeep Singh will be hosting a companion workshop that focuses on Python.

00:00:37.680 --> 00:00:43.160
Together, Ryan and I have worked with hundreds of data scientists and data enthusiasts, and

00:00:43.160 --> 00:00:48.439
we love to see how open-source data science combined with Posit's professional tools

00:00:48.439 --> 00:00:52.759
create powerful workflows that drive critical data science work.

00:00:52.759 --> 00:00:57.619
We also enjoy showing teens how our professional tools, like Posit Connect, can expand their

00:00:57.619 --> 00:01:03.000
data science capabilities beyond what they thought was possible. So here are our top

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:08.400
three reasons to join us for this year's Data Science Workflows with Posit Tools workshop

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:09.400
using R.

00:01:09.400 --> 00:01:15.559
Number one. Maybe you've already created shiny, actual reports with R Markdown or Quarto,

00:01:15.559 --> 00:01:21.239
and you're publishing those to Posit Connect. But there are lots of pieces that can go into

00:01:21.239 --> 00:01:27.919
these finished outputs and many ways to streamline and extend these pieces. We'll talk about

00:01:27.919 --> 00:01:35.080
ways to automate data ingestion, data validation, alerting and custom notifications to your

00:01:35.080 --> 00:01:40.680
stakeholders, model deployment, model versioning, and much more. End-to-end, when we string

00:01:40.680 --> 00:01:46.080
all the pieces together, you'll have exposure to powerful workflows and open-source packages

00:01:46.080 --> 00:01:49.959
that you can take back to your day-to-day job.

00:01:49.959 --> 00:01:54.839
Number two. Supercharging your own workflows is one thing, but data science is often a

00:01:54.839 --> 00:02:00.239
team effort. During this workshop, you'll get hands-on experience creating production-grade

00:02:00.239 --> 00:02:06.199
workflows that enable the sharing of assets and interoperability across teams and projects,

00:02:06.199 --> 00:02:09.479
no matter what programming language is being used.

00:02:09.479 --> 00:02:14.759
Number three. We like to keep things fun and provide everyone in the workshop with a safe

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:20.960
and engaging environment to ask whatever questions and explore new data science workflows. We'll

00:02:20.960 --> 00:02:25.080
also make sure to keep it relevant and use data that everyone in the workshop can relate

00:02:25.080 --> 00:02:26.759
to.

00:02:26.759 --> 00:02:31.080
Those are our top three reasons to join us for our workshop, and we look forward to seeing

00:02:31.080 --> 00:02:32.039
you in Chicago this summer.

